---
import RoomLayout from '../../../layouts/RoomLayout.astro';

const parts = [
  ['Origins', 'Chapters 1-5', 'Deep roots of the trust idea; the granting instruments; reception into state organic law; the trust-character question; the state\'s two capacities.'],
  ['Duties', 'Chapters 6-12', 'Loyalty; prudence and productivity; intergenerational impartiality; full value; self-dealing and exchanges; leasing; the duty to account.'],
  ['Enforcement', 'Chapters 13-18', 'Who may sue; the attorney-general problem; federal enforcement; justiciability; sovereign immunity; remedies.'],
  ['Reform', 'Chapters 19-20', 'Structural reform in the states; the model enforcement act, analyzed as a proposal.'],
  ['State appendices', '21 entries', 'One per covered state, each carrying its own authorities and verification queue.'],
];

const drafts = [
  {
    href: '/writing/hornbook/chapter-1/',
    label: 'Draft chapter',
    title: 'Chapter 2 - The Granting Instruments (formerly Chapter 1)',
    description:
      'The federal and state instruments that created the school-land grants and framed the long-running trust question.',
  },
  {
    href: '/writing/hornbook/trust-character/',
    label: 'Draft chapter',
    title: 'Chapter 4 - The Trust Character (formerly Chapter 3)',
    description:
      'The doctrinal question at the center of the field: whether school lands are enforceable trusts and what follows if they are.',
  },
  {
    href: '/writing/hornbook/nebraska-appendix/',
    label: 'Sample appendix',
    title: 'Appendix A - Nebraska',
    description:
      'A proving sample for the state appendix format, working backward from Nebraska cases into the national chapter structure.',
  },
];
---

<RoomLayout
  room="writing"
  title="School Trust Lands Hornbook"
  subtitle="The first one-volume treatise of American school-trust law, now a working edition."
  width="full"
  sourceId="hornbook-landing"
>
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none mt-8 prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <p class="hornbook-status">
      <strong>Working edition &mdash; June 2026.</strong> The treatise is complete in
      architecture &mdash; twenty chapters and twenty-one state appendices &mdash; and under
      active citation verification. <code>[VERIFY]</code> flags are shown
      honestly, and corrections are published as verification passes complete.
      <a href="/drafts/hornbook-working-edition-v1.docx" style="font-weight:600;">Download the working edition (Word, June 7, 2026) &rarr;</a>
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>School Trust Lands: The Law of America's Educational Land Trusts</em>
      is the Library's practitioner hornbook: a one-volume legal reference for
      lawyers, judges, trustees, agency staff, scholars, and public advocates who
      need the school-trust doctrine gathered in one place. It sits beside the
      narrative books in the Writing Room but has a different job. The books
      explain why the compact matters; the hornbook makes the law usable.
    </p>

    <p>
      The working architecture uses decimal section numbering, a two-footnote
      discipline for law and substrate notes, and an explicit verification
      protocol. Draft pages below preserve open flags rather than smoothing them
      away. That is deliberate: a founding legal reference should show readers
      which citations have passed verification and which still need a Legal
      Librarian's check.
    </p>

    <p class="hornbook-status">
      <strong>Corrections, June 7, 2026.</strong> This week's verification
      passes checked draft chapters against the primary case files now held in
      the Library's collection and corrected the text wherever a source did not
      support what the draft said. Corrections shipping with this update:
      Chapter 1 (the Mississippi case-law characterization &mdash; the word
      &ldquo;spoliation&rdquo; appears in neither leading opinion, and one of the two
      cases is in fact a counter-precedent; the 1785 and 1787 ordinance
      quotations now follow the original texts exactly), the Trust Character
      chapter (several quotation attributions and pin cites corrected against
      the opinions), and the Nebraska appendix (a corrected case citation and an
      unverified quotation converted to a flagged paraphrase). The working
      edition download carries all corrections to date.
    </p>
  </article>

  <section class="hornbook-drafts" aria-labelledby="drafts-heading">
    <h2 id="drafts-heading">Founding draft pages</h2>
    <div class="hornbook-card-grid">
      {drafts.map((draft) => (
        <a href={draft.href} class="hornbook-card">
          <span>{draft.label}</span>
          <h3>{draft.title}</h3>
          <p>{draft.description}</p>
          <strong>Read draft -&gt;</strong>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="hornbook-architecture" aria-labelledby="architecture-heading">
    <h2 id="architecture-heading">Architecture</h2>
    <div class="hornbook-parts">
      {parts.map(([part, title, description]) => (
        <article>
          <p>{part}</p>
          <h3>{title}</h3>
          <span>{description}</span>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="hornbook-onramp" aria-labelledby="onramp-heading">
    <h2 id="onramp-heading">For lawyers and legal librarians</h2>
    <p>
      The hornbook is also the on-ramp for the lawyer corps now forming around
      the Renewal program. Lawyers can start with the draft chapters, identify a
      citation or state appendix they can verify, and then move toward panel work
      through a bounded work sample.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/for-lawyers/">Lawyer on-ramp</a> ·
      <a href="/librarians/">Librarian corps</a> ·
      <a href="https://schooltrusts.org/renewal" rel="noopener">Renewal campus anteroom</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</RoomLayout>

<style>
  .hornbook-status {
    padding: 0.9rem 1rem;
    border: 1px solid #d6a84f;
    border-left: 4px solid #b7791f;
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: #fff8df;
    color: #422006;
  }
  .hornbook-drafts,
  .hornbook-architecture,
  .hornbook-onramp {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
  }
  .hornbook-drafts h2,
  .hornbook-architecture h2,
  .hornbook-onramp h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
    font-size: 1.45rem;
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .hornbook-card-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
  }
  .hornbook-card,
  .hornbook-parts article {
    display: block;
    border: 1px solid #d7dce4;
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: #fff;
    padding: 1.1rem;
  }
  .hornbook-card {
    text-decoration: none;
    color: inherit;
  }
  .hornbook-card:hover {
    border-color: #b88a2e;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 14px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.08);
  }
  .hornbook-card span,
  .hornbook-parts p {
    display: block;
    margin: 0 0 0.45rem;
    font-family: var(--font-sans, system-ui, sans-serif);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.09em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #64748b;
  }
  .hornbook-card h3,
  .hornbook-parts h3 {
    margin: 0 0 0.45rem;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: #0f172a;
  }
  .hornbook-card p,
  .hornbook-parts span,
  .hornbook-onramp p {
    color: #334155;
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .hornbook-card strong {
    color: #1d4ed8;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
  }
  .hornbook-parts {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(260px, 1fr));
    gap: 0.85rem;
  }
</style>
